From: Jarod Malestein <jarod@umich.edu>
User-Agent: Thunderbird 1.5.0.5 (Windows/20060719)
MIME-Version: 1.0
To: cosign-announce@umich.edu
Subject: IISCoSign 2.0.0 now available
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit


Version 2.0.0 of IISCoSign is now available for download from 
http://weblogin.org

Besides multi-factor support, the biggest change is the new schema for 
the cosign.dll.config files.  Included in the zip file is a sample 
config file with an explanation of the new layout.

Here is a list of changes from the last official release, 1.1.1:

1.2.0
+ Kerberos ticket retrieving -- IISCoSign can now retrieve and store 
Kerberos 5 tickets (if allowed by the weblogin server).
+ Load failure mode -- If an occurs while IISCoSign is loading or 
verifying a user, it will prevent the web site from serving content.

1.5.0 -
+ Multi-factor authentication support -- Support for other 
authentication methods.  The authentication factors are made available 
through the server variable HTTP_COSIGN_FACTORS.
+ Validating config file independent of loading filter, xml schema for 
config file. -- The filter now verifies the config file against a schema 
and reports any misconfiguration information to the Event Viewer.

2.0.0 -
+ Apache style protected/unprotected/protected configuration -- There 
are now three directives for a URL: <Protected>, <AllowPublicAccess>, 
and <Unprotected>.  <Unprotected> is used to override an earlier 
<Protected> or <AllowPublicAccess> tag.  So, for example: /a could be 
protected, but /a/b could be unprotected.

+ SiteEntry support -- When a user logs in for the first time, this 
option will redirect the user to the specified 'splash' or 'main menu' 
page of your web app.
+ PostErrorRedirect support -- If a user is redirected to a weblogin 
server and he was POSTing, the user is redirected to this warning page 
to let them know there will be lost data.

Finally, thanks to everyone who helped test the 2.0.0 beta!

Please send comments or questions to cosign@umich.edu or 
cosign.discuss@umich.edu.

--Jarod Malestein


